    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Licensing Bicycles Seems a Good Next Step</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Graham B Rothaus letter on May 14 letters responding to April 30 article suggests all teenage and adult bike riders in New York City be licensed (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the letters (May 14) responding to the article ''Using a Bicycle Helmet and the Head Inside'' (April 30), no one mentions requiring that all bicycles ridden by teenagers and adults be licensed. Most bicyclists are no longer using bicycles for pleasure, but for work. Are we better than the Scandinavians, Dutch, Israelis, and how many other countries that require licensing?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the letters (May 14) responding to the article ''Using a Bicycle Helmet and the Head Inside'' (April 30), no one mentions requiring that all bicycles ridden by teenagers and adults be licensed. Most bicyclists are no longer using bicycles for pleasure, but for work. Are we better than the Scandinavians, Dutch, Israelis, and how many other countries that require licensing?</p>
        <p>It's bad enough when pedestrians ignore the laws of crossing, but at least we walk more slowly. And the bladers go so fast on the pavement and all over the streets. If they don't  follow the rules they too should be licensed.</p>
        <p>GRAHAM B. ROTHAUS  Rose Hill</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
